<F P=100> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th Announces Postponement of Upcoming Cairo Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2602103194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0930 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2602103194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 26 Feb (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, adviser to 
Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat and head of the Palestinian 
delegation to negotiations with Israel for the implementation of 
the temporary self-rule in Gaza and Jericho first, has announced 
that the next round of Palestinian-Israeli talks, scheduled to 
take place in Cairo Monday, has been postponed until after the 
Palestinian leadership has determined its position on U.S. 
President Bill Clinton's invitation to talks in Washington. 
  He told MENA that he and the Palestinian delegation will 
leave for Tunis Sunday morning to meet with the Palestinian 
leadership under the chairmanship of president 'Arafat to decide 
on a response to the U.S. President's invitation. 
  What matters is not the venue of the talks, he said; the 
talks in Egypt, both in Cairo or Taba, were going very well, and 
Egypt is providing all possible support, Sha'th explained. 
  The issue is not where we negotiate but what we negotiate, 
he 
said. He urged international protection for the Palestinian 
people in accordance with the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of 
Principles reached in Oslo. 
  Dr. Sha'th accused the Israeli Army of colluding with the 
Israeli settlers who carried out the criminal massacre and the 
horrible killings in the al-Ibrahimi Mosque in Hebron at dawn 
yesterday. 
  Without genuine protection against the Israeli settlers, the 
Palestinian people will face daily massacres, he said. 
  These criminal acts, Sha'th added, cannot be perpetrated by 
individuals. He noted the bad emotional climate and the 
collusion of the Israeli Army with the perpetrators of massacres. 
  Sha'th wondered where the Israeli Army was, which usually 
fills the plazas of the al-Ibrahimi Mosque. He noted that the 
Palestinians pray daily in the mosque under the guns of the 
Israelis. Where was the Israeli Army at the time of the 
massacre, he wondered. 
  Sha'th stressed that eight worshipers were killed by Israeli 
Army gunfire at the mosque's entrance while trying to leave. 
  Sha'th stressed the need for reconsidering the form, method, 
and demands of the Israeli negotiators. 
  He pointed out that two-thirds of the draft security 
agreement worked out during the talks in Cairo and Taba deal 
with Israeli demands for the protection of settlers. It is the 
Palestinian people that really need protection, he stressed. 
  Sha'th said: We demand international protection for the 
Palestinian people, because this is part of the Oslo agreement, 
and Israel cannot reject it. He noted that Israel has so far 
been procrastinating in accepting such protection. 
  Concluding, Sha'th stressed that the next 
Palestinian-Israeli 
negotiations will mainly focus on international protection for 
the Palestinian people so that the criminal massacre and the 
horrible killings will not recur. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12328 </DOCNO>
