<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   President, Others Comment on Church Bombing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Information Minister Comments </H4>
<F P=102> NC2702231594 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 2211 GMT 27 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2702231594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Information Minister Michel Samahah, followed </F>
by a question and answer session, with unidentified 
correspondents in Beirut 27 February--live or recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Samahah] At the invitation of his excellency 
the prime minister, the Council of Ministers held an 
extraordinary meeting this evening. His excellency the 
president attended and chaired the meeting. 
  The Council of Ministers devoted its extraordinary meeting 
to 
the attack against state security, which took the form of an 
explosion at the Sayyidat al-Najat Church in Zuq Mikha'il this 
morning. At the beginning of the meeting, his excellency the 
president briefed the ministers on his contacts with Syrian 
President Hafiz al-Asad, who denounced the attack and placed 
Syria's resources at the disposal of Lebanese authorities to 
discover the perpetrators. He also briefed the ministers on his 
contact with his majesty the king of Jordan for the same 
purpose. His excellency the president also briefed the Council 
of Ministers on all his contacts from within the country and 
abroad denouncing the attack. 
  The Council of Ministers then examined the implications of 
the crime and its intention to weaken confidence in the security 
situation and the economic and social stability in Lebanon, fan 
sectarian fanaticism in the country, and divert the attention of 
world public opinion from the massacre committed by Israel in 
the Ibrahimi Mosque in Hebron in the occupied Palestinian 
territory. The Council of Ministers praised the overwhelming 
reaction through which the Lebanese expressed comprehensive 
national unity in the face of this attack that was directed 
against the country's security and unity. 
  The Council of Ministers decided to refer the attack against 
the state security in the Sayyidat al-Najat Church in Zuq 
Mikha'il to the Judicial Council. Following the statement 
issued by his excellency the president, the speaker of the 
Chamber of Deputies, and the prime minister this morning calling 
for public mourning tomorrow, the Council of Ministers also 
decided to call for a general strike tomorrow. [passage omitted] 
  [Correspondent] [Question indistinct]? 
  [Samahah] There are measures that are being adopted by the 
security commands in all the areas at the instructions of the 
Council of Ministers and the ministers concerned. 
  [Correspondent] Mr. Minister, [words indistinct] the crime 
that took place, have you specified the [words indistinct]? 
  [Samahah] All that was said by the officials today refers to 
whoever we think, and we can confirm, is behind this attack, 
crime, massacre this morning against the worshipers in Sayyidat 
al-Najat Church. 
  [Correspondent] Mr. Minister, [words indistinct] referred to 
those who opposed the pope's visit to Lebanon. You hoped that 
they had no hand in the church explosion. Did you mean Minister 
Walid Junblatt? 
  [Samahah] Not at all. Minister Walid Junblatt is one of 
those who has welcomed the visit of his holiness the pope and 
has cooperated with the Lebanese authorities. He has adopted 
declared positions with regard to domestic unity and receiving 
the pope in Lebanon. The ones I meant know who they are. They 
issued statements on this matter last week. 
  [Correspondent] [Question indistinct]? 
  [Samahah] Perhaps. Let us leave it to the investigation to 
determine that. We hope it will end soon and that the 
perpetrators will be discovered soon so that everyone will be 
reassured and we can know the aim and background of this attack. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

