<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister, Official, Parties React to Hebron Event </TI></H3>
<H4>   Deputy Speaker Comments </H4>
<F P=102> NC2502202294 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 1630 GMT 25 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2502202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chamber of Deputies Speaker Nabih Birri said that 
the Hebron Mosque shootings is another chapter in the record of 
Zionist terrorism and is an incentive to unite and insist on 
liberating the land. He called for escalating resistance to the 
Israeli occupation forces. He stressed that Israel does not 
seek peace in the region and that its attempts to circumvent the 
Geneva summit are continuing, sometimes by threatening to repeat 
last summer's aggression and at other times by imposing 
obstructionist conditions to withdrawal from south Lebanon and 
implementation of Resolution 425. 
  For his part, Prime Minister Rafiq al-Hariri has called for 
collective action to end the occupation. He affirmed that a 
comprehensive and just peace is the means to achieve a genuine 
peace and noted that any partial agreement in the name of peace 
will only lead to further conflict and the shedding of innocent 
people's blood. 
  The Amal Movement urged international legitimacy to prove 
its 
credibility and enforce the implementation of its resolutions, 
which Israel violates daily. 
  The Progressive Socialist Party viewed the massacre as a 
message to the Arabs and Muslims and another disgrace for 
Zionism, which world public opinion acquitted of charges of 
racism at the United Nations. 
  The National Liberal Party denounced the massacre and 
expressed fear of its negative impact on the peace process. 

</TEXT>

