<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Formation of Government Excluding YSP Rumored </TI></H3>
<H4>   Al-Iryani Reportedly To Head Government </H4>
<F P=102> PM2502154594 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 25 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2502154594 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Abdallah Hammudah: "Al-Iryani Proposed To Head a </F>
Yemeni Government Excluding Socialist Party"] 
  [Excerpt] London, Sanaa, Aden, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- 
Well-informed sources in the Yemeni capital have said that there 
are rumors about the possibility of entrusting Dr. 'Abd-al-Karim 
al-Iryani with forming a national unity government whose task is 
to implement the Pledge and Accord Document. However, political 
sources close to the Yemeni Socialist party [YSP] leadership 
stressed that "the party refuses to participate in such a 
government." They expressed their confidence that all the other 
parties would not join a government that includes the General 
People's Congress [GPC] and the Yemeni Reform Grouping [YRG] and 
excludes the party, because "it would be a partitionist 
government by all standards." 
  This comes in the context of reports that President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih wishes to end the present coalition by excluding 
the YSP, relying on the parliamentary majority the GPC and YRG 
enjoy in the House of Representatives. Especially as former 
South Yemen President 'Ali Nasir Muhammad turned down a YSP 
offer to head a new government in place of the present 
government headed by Haydar Abu-Bakr al-'Attas. 
  An opposition sources share the view of a high-ranking YSP 
official that "anyone can form a secessionist government if he 
wants to." But the main current issue is to safeguard unity. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

