<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says No Talks Without Guarantees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0103065494 Paris AFP in English 0201 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0103065494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, March 1 (AFP)--The PLO leadership decided 
late Monday [28 February] not to resume talks with Israel until 
it gets security guarantees for Palestinians, an authoritative 
source here said, amid reports of "hopeful signs" from the 
United Nations. 
  Samir Ghawshah, a member of the Palestine Liberation 
Organisation's executive committee, emerged from the committee's 
second meeting here in two days to say that there would be no 
resumption of talks until there were guarantees of security and 
"international protection" for the Palestinians. 
  The decision casts doubt on the invitation by US President 
Bill Clinton to both sides to begin accelerated talks in 
Washington on Wednesday to speed up the peace process. Israel 
has accepted Clinton's initiative. 
  Monday's session, under the chairmanship of PLO leader Yasir 
'Arafat, lasted two and a half hours, but was adjourned until 
later Tuesday to await the outcome of a United Nations Security 
Council debate on the massacre, Ghawshah said. 
  That debate, held over from Saturday amid sharp disagreement 
between the PLO and the United States, was due to have begun 
around 0100 GMT Tuesday (8:00 p.m. Monday in New York). 
  Madeleine Albright, the US ambassador to the United Nations, 
said in New York that negotiations prior to the debate were 
"going well." 
  The current Security Council chairman, Roble Olhaye of 
Djibouti, said the delegations had "accomplished a lot" and that 
there were "hopeful signs for a resolution." 
  The PLO's representative at the United Nations, Nasir 
al-Qidwah, said he might well address the council, and that the 
Americans would not stand in his way, as they often did. 
  Talks in the Council snagged Saturday on Washington's 
opposition to PLO demands that the UN send an international 
peacekeeping force to the occupied territories, a move rejected 
by Israel. 
  PLO leaders have also slammed as "inadequate" Israeli 
pledges 
to disarm the most extreme of the Jewish settlers in the 
occupied territories, in the wake of Friday's massacre of 52 
Muslim worshippers in the West Bank town of Hebron. 
  They want all settlers disarmed, an unreasonable demand in 
the eyes of the Israelis, who point to continuing attacks on 
settlers by Muslim extremists. 
  Israeli premier Yitzhaq Rabin announced in Jerusalem on 
Monday that Israel would accept the deployment of an 
international civilian force in the occupied territories. 
  "We would accept the stationing of an international presence 
in Gaza and Jericho, but it should not consist of military 
forces and should comply with the Oslo Declaration of 
Principles" on Palestinian self-rule signed last September, 
Rabin told representatives of American Jewish organisations. 
  But another PLO executive committee member 'Ali Ishaq told 
AFP after Monday's session that Rabin's offer was "derisory". 
  The PLO's mainstream Fatah movement announced Monday that it 
had ended the ceasefire it declared to celebrate the historic 
September 13 accord with Israel on limited Palestinian autonomy 
in the Gaza Strip and the West Bank town of Jericho. 
  Shortly afterwards its Fatah Falcons guerrillas claimed 
responsibility for the murder of an 80-year-old Israeli who was 
hacked to death with an axe at Kfar Saba north of Tel Aviv. 
  Fatah supporters paraded in the Dayr Balah refugee camp in 
the Gaza Strip on Monday evening to claim the murder as an act 
of revenge. 
  Ghawshah also said the PLO leadership had resolved to 
increase its diplomatic activity to win worldwide backing for 
its demands, by making representations to the Arab nations, the 
non-aligned movement, the Russians, the Americans and the 
Europeans. 
  Three Arab delegations pulled out of talks with Israel in 
Washington on Sunday in protest at the massacre, after PLO 
leader Yasir 'Arafat criticised the Israeli army for failing to 
stop US-born doctor Barukh Goldstein emptying three and a half 
clips from his Galil automatic rifle into the worshippers. 
  And the Arab League council in Cairo on Sunday framed an 
uncompromising resolution blaming Israel for the attack. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

