<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-Rabbuh on `Prerequisites' for Resuming Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2802203694 Tunis Tunis-7 Television in Arabic 1900 GMT 28 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tunis Tunis-7 Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Exclusive" statement by Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh, head of the </F>
PLO's Information Department, "a while ago"; place not given] 
  [Text] The Palestinian leadership will be meeting this 
evening in order to examine a number of topics revolving around 
the situation in the aftermath of the Hebron massacre. 
  At the forefront of these topics is the issue of sending 
envoys to Washington to examine a number of matters, 
particularly the need to guarantee international protection for 
the Palestinian people, as well as the need to take effective 
measures to disarm the settlers, to remove a number of 
settlements which have been hotbeds of tension, and criminal 
activities against the Palestinian people. These are necessary 
prerequisites before the resumption of the peace process, which 
came into being in order to provide security for the Palestinian 
people and the rest of the region's peoples. However, such 
security has been violated by armed gangs of settlers. 
  Moreover, the measures which were taken yesterday by the 
Israeli Government do not constitute a practical step but merely 
an exercise to cover up the crime. For this reason, curbing the 
activities of settlers and the building of settlements in 
general, and the provision of international protection are 
fundamental requirements for the negotiations to take their 
natural course. 
  Conversely, we have also been trying to table these issues 
before the UN Security Council; we are hoping that a resolution, 
which would guarantee international protection and the 
disarmament of settlers, will be adopted in an effort by the 
international community to help us to continue the peace process 
to its final conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

