<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres: Extreme Right `Enemies of the People' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2802141794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1300 GMT 28 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2802141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin said we have suffered 
a heavy blow in international public opinion in the wake of the 
Hebron massacre, but he hopes it will not last long and tourism 
to Israel will not be harmed. The prime minister told Labor's 
caucus that it is Israel's aim to bring about gradual calm 
because in the final analysis the solution to the problem is 
political. We will, however, continue to act against 
Palestinian terrorism and Jewish extremists. The prime minister 
stressed that Israel is determined to uphold the agreements with 
the PLO and to continue the negotiations. 
  Our correspondent Yo'el Nir reports that Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres sharply attacked right-wing extremists at the 
caucus meeting. Peres expressed shock not only at the appalling 
massacre, but also the rejoicing and gloating by the extreme 
right. What is most frightening is that Qiryat Arba' is a 
hotbed for the murder; we have no dialogue with those people, 
Peres said. They can cause a terrible catastrophe to the Jewish 
people, they are the enemies of the people, and they have to be 
treated like enemies. The man who perpetrated the massacre in 
the Cave of the Patriarchs has been damned to hell. His 
cohorts, who are now strutting like peacocks, have to have their 
weapons confiscated, and a series of measures have to be taken 
against them in order to prevent them from causing more damage 
and we must not hesitate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

