<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet `Majority' Said To Favor Removing Hebron Jews </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2802190494 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1800 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2802190494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen] </F>
  [Text] For the first time ever, Israel is prepared to 
allow the deployment of forces under international supervision 
in Gaza and Jericho. This emerged this evening in consultations 
held by the prime minister and the foreign minister. A check 
conducted by our correspondent reveals that a majority is 
emerging in the cabinet in favor of evacuating the settlers from 
the heart of Hebron. Our political correspondent 'Imanu'el 
Rosen reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Rosen] Shim'on Peres set the tone in 
yesterday's cabinet session, when he called on his fellow 
ministers to comply with the new demands of the Palestinians. 
Today he reiterated as much it in public. 
  [Peres] To the extent that their demands are sensible, they 
will be examined. For example, if the Palestinians say the size 
of the police force must be increased, I believe it is a 
legitimate demand which requires pointed discussion. 
  [Rosen] It is now clear that the cabinet's decisions are not 
enough, and that the PLO will have to be given more. Some 
ministers, including hawks such as Ya'aqov Tzur, argue that much 
more than 30 settlers must be disarmed and their movements must 
be restricted. 
  More radical proposals have been floated in the cabinet. For 
example, there apparently is a majority in favor of evacuating 
the settlers from Bet Hadasa, Bet Romano, and Tall al-Rumaythah 
in Hebron. Half the cabinet ministers are unequivocally in 
favor of such a move: The four ministers of Meretz -- Shulamit 
Aloni, Ya'ir Tzaban, Yosi Sarid, and Amnon Rubinstein -- as well 
as Binyamin Ben-Eli'ezer, Yisra'el Qeysar, 'Uzi Bar'am, and 
Mikha Harish, who makes his consent conditional on such a demand 
coming from the defense establishment. 
  Three ministers oppose it: Shim'on Shetrit, Ya'aqov Tzur, 
and Ora Namir. The latter favors such a move, but does not 
believe it is feasible. 
  Two other ministers, Moshe Shahal and Shim'on Peres, refused 
to answer. One minister, David Liba'i, said he is not 
knowledgeable on the matter. Nevertheless, it is hard to see 
any of them voting against such a proposal if it is raised. 
  We could not obtain the answer of Minister Avraham Shohat. 
Yitzhaq Rabin is opposed to reopening the Declaration of 
Principles, but it is not certain that he perceives the 
evacuation of Hebron as falling in that category. When we asked 
him about it today, he replied: I am not prepared to elaborate. 
[end recording] 
  [Later in the broadcast, the announcer adds: "The Council of 
Jewish Settlements in Judaea, Samaria, and Gaza is furious at 
our report that most ministers are in favor of removing the 
settlers from the heart of Hebron." In a recorded passage, 
local settlement leader Elyaqim Ha'etzni states: "If they touch 
any settlement, including the Jewish settlement in Hebron, all 
of us to the last man will prevent it. Nobody will stay alone 
here. Not even one brick will be removed from this edifice. 
Let this much be clear. We will be followed in our footsteps 
by every Jewish patriot in Eretz Yisra'el. Indeed, all of us 
here will not allow them to tear us apart one by one. They will 
not start with Hebron, which may very well be the most precious 
of all our settlements."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

