<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   High State of Alert Reported North of Jerusalem </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0103092694 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 1 Mar 94 pp 
1, 19 </F>

<F P=103> TA0103092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Roni Shaqed and Shim'on Schiffer] </F>
  [Excerpt] Wide-ranging security measures have been taken 
around the country for fear of retaliatory terrorist attacks in 
the wake of the Hebron massacre. 
  IDF [Israel Defense Forces] sources warned the secretariats 
of settlements belonging to the Mate Binyamin Regional Council 
[between Jerusalem and Ramallah] of terrorist plans to 
perpetrate a spectacular attack against one or more of the 
settlements there. A very high state of alert was declared in 
the Mate Binyamin settlements, and the IDF has dramatically 
beefed up its forces in the region. 
  A particularly sharp pamphlet published yesterday by the 
Palestinian command in the territories, which includes PLO 
representatives, said: "The Zionist enemy must be aware that no 
crime goes unavenged. Those who spill the blood of our people 
will not go unscathed. We will set the ground under the feet of 
the Nazi occupiers on fire." 
  The Palestinian leadership in the territories has renewed 
the 
activities of the Unified National Leadership of the Intifadah, 
in cooperation with Fatah, and called for the resumption of 
intifadah activities, including violence against IDF forces and 
settlers, in order to cause as many casualties and as much 
damage to property as possible. As will be recalled, the 
command was disbanded after the signing of the Washington 
agreement in September, but it was reestablished on Sunday. 
  Sources in the territories noted that the command was 
reestablished with the cooperation of Fatah representatives and 
that its demands are a signal to 'Arafat that conducting 
negotiations does not mean control on the ground. The sources 
said that as a result of the erosion in 'Arafat's status, he has 
no choice but to radicalize his positions and to accept the 
demands of the leadership in the territories. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

