<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab League Chief, Somali Leader Discuss Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0203121694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1135 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0203121694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 2 Mar (MENA)--Arab League Secretary General 
Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid today conferred with Somali Interim 
President Ali Mahdi Mohamed, who is visiting Cairo. The two 
officials discussed the Arab League's role in finding a peaceful 
settlement to the Somali crisis, especially after the withdrawal 
of foreign troops. 
  Speaking afterward, Mohamed said he and the secretary 
general 
reviewed basic issues relating to the crisis in Somalia. He 
noted that the Arab League has always been in the lead in its 
efforts to resolve this crisis. He added that 12 Somali faction 
leaders are visiting Cairo at the invitation of President 
Mubarak to hold talks that seek to rescue the Somali people. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid stated that they reviewed the recent 
developments in Somalia and praised the role undertaken by 
President Mubarak to achieve national reconciliation and resolve 
the Somali crisis. He noted that the Arab League is eager to 
consolidate any role that may help the Somali people emerge from 
their predicament. He added that a meeting with the remaining 
Somali faction leaders visiting Cairo will be held on Sunday at 
the Arab League headquarters. 

</TEXT>

