<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th on Tunis Talks, U.S., Observers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0103121594 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 1045 GMT 1 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0103121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political </F>
adviser to PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat, in Tunis, by Sa'id 
Mu'addi, in the studio, date not given; from the "With the 
Midday Events" program--recorded] 
  [Text] [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, currently in Tunis, good 
evening. 
  [Sha'th] Good evening. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Sha'th, what is your initial reaction to the 
government's decision to release approximately 1,000 detainees 
and prisoners from the West Bank and Gaza Strip? 
  [Sha'th] Naturally, one wants freedom for all his fellow 
citizens and people. We have worked determinedly at the table 
of negotiations to secure the release of all Palestinian 
detainees and not to keep any of our children in prisons and 
detention camps. This is a duty that we must pursue. When any 
citizen is released, this means that freedom has been restored 
to a human being who has suffered gravely. However, as you 
know, this move is one of the results of this horrendous 
massacre which claimed many lives in the Ibrahimi Mosque in 
Hebron. I believe that besides releasing those detainees, many 
things must be done in order to safeguard our people and prevent 
the recurrence of such dreadful massacres. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, you are taking part in the PLO 
leadership's consultations. Are there final decisions? 
  [Sha'th] The meetings are continuing tonight. They have been 
going on for two days. This is because the incident was so 
grave and the responsibility is so heavy. We should continue 
work to provide protection for our Palestinian people. 
Therefore, the final results of these meetings will not appear 
before the end of tonight. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil, what is the PLO leadership's trend 
regarding the resumption of the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations? 
  [Sha'th] This is one of the important questions which we 
must 
decide tonight. Russian President Yeltsin has sent a high-level 
envoy. He asked us to await his arrival before arriving at our 
final decision. We will respect this wish. We are waiting to 
meet with this envoy before we arrive at results, especially 
with regard to the negotiations. Naturally, we do not want to 
halt the peace process, which will eventually bring about 
Israeli withdrawal and freedom for our people. However, we are 
fully aware that important, sufficient, and necessary guarantees 
must be provided for the peace process. We are responsible for 
our people and for their freedom, security, and protection. 
This makes the decision difficult and guarantees necessary. 
  [Mu'addi] When will the Palestinian delegation leave for 
Washington for talks with the U.S. Administration on the 
resumption of the negotiations? 
  [Sha'th] Soon. I believe that what is required now is to 
hold consultations with the U.S. Administration to provide these 
guarantees. As I have already mentioned, there will also be 
consultations with the Russian Government. There are other 
consultations with the Arab, European, and other world 
governments. What is required, effectively, is to have the 
international community assume its responsibility and to agree 
on measures for the protection of the peace process through 
providing security for our people. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil, one last question. Israel has agreed in 
principle on the presence of international observers in Jericho 
and Gaza. What is your comment? 
  [Sha'th] This is an important move. It is referred to in the 
Declaration of Principles [DOP], which we signed in Washington. 
The DOP provides for a temporary international presence. 
Naturally, we want any international presence to be only 
temporary; that is, until withdrawal is completed, the 
Palestinian police assume their responsibilities, and until we 
reach a solution that ensures security and peace for all sons of 
our people. Therefore, this move is necessary and important. 
It must provide the minimum level of protection. The other 
point, which is equally important, is the removal of the causes 
which led to this odious crime, primarily those settlers who 
carry weapons and open fire wherever they go. These are two very 
important conditions for providing protection and for the 
prevalence of security and stability so that the peace process 
can maintained. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, currently in Tunis, thank you 
very much. 
  [Sha'th] Thank you, brother. Thank you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

