<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hamas Executes DFLP Aide as `Israeli Agent' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2802145994 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 25 Feb 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM2802145994 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jamal Khashuqji: "Hamas Executed DFLP Leader in </F>
Gaza"] 
  [Excerpt] Jeddah -- Relations between the Islamic 
Resistance Movement (Hamas) and the Democratic Front for the 
Liberation of Palestine [DFLP] have deteriorated seriously after 
Hamas announced that its armed squads in Gaza executed Yusuf 
Abu-Lafi, head of the DFLP military organ in the Gaza Strip. 
  In a statement issued by "the 'Izz-al-Din al-Qassam squads," 
Hamas accused Abu-Lafi (27 years) of having been "an Israeli 
agent." It distributed a videotape of his confessions. 
  The incident marks a further deterioration in the relations 
between the two parties, which are members of the Damascus-based 
Alliance of Palestinian Forces [APF] opposed to Palestinian 
President Yasir 'Arafat. 
  Hamas's official spokesman in Jordan Muhammad Nazzal has 
stated that the DFLP's protest against the execution of the head 
of its military organ in Gaza was strange. He told AL-HAYAH 
that the videotape and the confessions of Yusuf Abu-Lafi "were 
sufficient explanation." He stressed that Hamas had given the 
factions allied with it, especially the DFLP, the details 
pertaining to that issue. He added: "It is the general policy 
of Hamas to inform the faction to which an uncovered agent 
belongs of the details, and it will continue to do so." He 
emphasized that "purging the Palestinian factions of agents is 
one of the important programs which all factions should 
cooperate with it to fulfill." 
  The DFLP, however, has protested the incident and described 
the dead man as "a revolutionary commander and a patriotic 
struggler known to the masses of the Khan Yunis camp as one of 
their righteous sons." That came in a DFLP memorandum 
submitted to the APF leadership during its meeting in Damascus 
last Saturday requesting an end to such incidents. 
  Before Hamas claimed responsibility for killing Abu-Lafi, 
the 
DFLP in the Gaza Strip issued several statements describing 
Abu-Lafi as "an honorable struggler" abducted "while performing 
a struggle duty." They accused the abductors of being "agents 
of the occupation authorities" and threatened revenge if he was 
harmed. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

