<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli Government Measures Termed `Insufficient' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0103183394 Jerusalem AL-NAHAR in Arabic 28 Feb 94 pp 3, 7 </F>
<F P=103> TA0103183394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-NAHAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "The Crime and the Results"] </F>
  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] The cycles of violence which 
the Palestinian territories are witnessing raise a great deal of 
doubt about the continuation of the talks or implementation of 
the accord. While Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin has 
always accused radical Muslims of trying to derail the peace 
accord by attacking Israelis, in the wake of the Hebron crime it 
has been proved that the responsibility falls on the shoulders 
of racist Israeli settlers. Rabin's government must confront 
those narrow-minded people and put an end to their provocations. 
Although in yesterday's cabinet session the Israeli Government 
took some steps to restrict the settlers' movements, those steps 
are insufficient to reassure us of what will happen tomorrow. 
The feeling of dejection among our people can only be overcome 
by measures aimed at restraining the settlers, disarming them, 
and preventing them from carrying out provocative acts against 
Palestinians. 
  Although the Palestinian-Israeli accord represented a 
political breakthrough between the two peoples, we are not 
misrepresenting the facts when we say that the deterioration of 
the situation, the nonimplementation of the accord on its dates, 
and Israel's attempt to extract more concessions from the 
Palestinian side were all factors that contributed to a setback 
and erosion of international fervor for the accord. 
Undoubtedly, the accord will be in danger of collapse unless 
Israel takes immediate steps to implement it without waiting for 
agreements on details. It is impossible to reach a finalized 
solution and agreement on all the clauses. The dangers 
surrounding the accord require one to bet on goodwill and begin 
implementing the accord. They also require the commitment of 
the two parties to address the economic concerns in the Gaza 
Strip and Jericho. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

