<H3> <TI>   BABIL on U.S. `Domination' of UNSC Operating Mechanisms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0203132694 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1100 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0203132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, 2 Mar (INA)--The newspaper BABIL asserts 
that the UN Security Council [UNSC] resolutions on Somalia and 
Bosnia-Herzegovina are flagrant evidence of the deteriorating 
credibility and role of the United Nations. They are testimony 
to the immense U.S. domination of the UNSC's operating 
mechanisms and decisionmaking process. 
  In an article published today, the paper adds: The U.S. 
moves to obstruct the passage of a resolution condemning the 
Zionist entity and authorizing the deployment of international 
observers in the occupied Arab territories to protect the 
Palestinians show the immense U.S. domination of the world body 
and the UNSC, and demonstrate the urgent need to restore balance 
to the UNSC-- something impossible to achieve as long as the 
UNSC remains hostage to U.S. wishes. 
  BABIL goes on to say: The U.S. treatment of the UNSC is a 
clear message to all those who expect the "cosponsors of the 
conference" to find a solution to the Palestinian people's 
ordeal. For the judge is the very culprit, whose hands are 
stained with the blood of our people in both Iraq and Palestine. 
  BABIL recalls the rapidity with which the UNSC passed its 
anti-Iraq resolutions in August 1990, when it passed three 
resolutions in a single week. Together, these resolutions 
contained 18 paragraphs, the implementation of which is 
mandatory. 
  The paper concludes by saying: This is how the United States 
handled the Iraq issue and pushed the UNSC to pass a series of 
unfair resolutions in an unprecedented manner. 

</TEXT>

