<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Downplays Syria's Granting Exit Visas to Jews </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2602172694 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 25 Feb 94 p A1 </F>
<F P=103> TA2602172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Aqiva Eldar, Aluf Ben, Lili Galili, and news </F>
agencies] 
  [Excerpts] Damascus has issued exit visas to all the 1,000 
Jews who remained in Syria, and they are now allowed to leave 
the country if they so wish, Yosef Jatti, the deputy chief rabbi 
of Syria, stated yesterday. 
  Diplomats said this was yet another gesture of good will on 
the part of the Syrian Government in a bid to improve its 
relations with the United States and promote the peace process 
in the Middle East. [passage omitted] 
  Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres stated yesterday that Israel 
still needs a gesture on the part of the Syrian president that 
will prove the seriousness of his intentions with regard to 
peace. 
  "If we are talking about confidence-building measures, then 
these measures are too small to build the necessary confidence," 
Peres commented yesterday. 
  "The release of Jews or the willingness to issue them 
passports are nothing new. We would like to see something more 
serious, along the lines of a public declaration such as: `I 
want to make peace with Israel,' as al-Sadat did; or conversely, 
a visit to Israel or public negotiations on all levels," Peres 
said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

