<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin, Slovenia's Kucan Discuss Balkan Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103172094 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1430 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0103172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Milan Kucan today will end his three-day 
official visit to Israel, where he attended the 4th 
international business forum as a guest. Vojko Plevel reports 
that he met with Israeli Prime Minister Yithzaq Rabin this 
morning: 
  [Begin Plevel recording] After yesterday's meeting with 
Israeli President Ezer Weizman and two meetings with Israeli 
Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres, President Kucan also met with 
Israeli Prime Minister Yithzaq Rabin this morning. The two 
exchanged views and assessments on the current international 
situation, especially the circumstances in the Middle East and 
in the Balkans and, naturally, in Europe. They both agreed that 
the belief that the mere collapse of the Berlin Wall would 
resolve the situation in Europe proved to be an illusion and 
that we need to further strengthen our efforts to assert 
democracy as an alternative to war, as well as equality of 
smaller and less developed nations. Russia remains the biggest 
puzzle, to which recent events can attest. 
  Regarding bilateral contacts and possibilities for their 
strengthening, President Kucan after these talks assessed that 
with the Israeli partners he found understanding and interest 
for Slovenia that exceeded a mere bilateral interest. They have 
also shown an interest to intercede on behalf of our economic 
and political interests in their international contacts, 
especially where international policy is being decided and where 
they are present because of their specific position. They also 
fully support our efforts for integration into Partnership for 
Peace, which they, just like ourselves, assess as preparation 
for a new collective security system in the world. 
  President Kucan will end his visit to Israel this afternoon 
with a speech at the 4th international forum in Jerusalem. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12540 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes041_l_94022" </HT>


