<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-041 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Turns Down Arms Request </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0203095594 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 2 Mar 94 p A9 </F>
<F P=103> TA0203095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpt] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin yesterday met in his 
office in Jerusalem with Slovenian President Milan Kucan and 
turned down his request to buy weapons from Israel. Rabin 
explained to Kucan that Israel will continue to abide by the 
international arms embargo on the former Yugoslav republics and 
will not sell weapons to Slovenia at this stage. 
  The Slovenian president told Rabin his country is 
experiencing great difficulties due to the war in neighboring 
Bosnia, as well as the sanctions and the embargo on the region, 
and asked him to enhance security relations between Slovenia and 
Israel. 
  The prime minister told Kucan that Israel understands and 
supports the desire of small nations to conduct an independent 
life. Israel will be prepared to hold contacts on 
security-related issues and examine various proposals for 
cooperation with Slovenia, but will under no circumstances 
whatsoever violate the sanctions and the embargo, Rabin said. 
"Once the embargo and the sanctions are lifted, we can 
definitely discuss the strengthening of security relations," the 
prime minister promised the visitor. I hope our two countries 
will strengthen their relations and will soon be able to sign 
cooperation agreements on economic issues, investment 
protection, and tourism. 
  Slovenia has over the last few months been in contact with 
Israeli elements to buy antiaircraft systems. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

