<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Pressure Said Behind Test Launch </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0103194994 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0103194994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by army affairs correspondent Alon Ben-David] </F>
  [Text] There has been yet another mishap in a test 
launching of the Arrow missile. A malfunctioning occurred 
during the seventh test launching of the Arrow missile. The 
project directors believe that the malfunctioning is in the 
missile's ground control system and has nothing to do with the 
missile itself. Our army affairs correspondent Alon Ben-David 
is here with more details: 
  This morning's experiment was supposed to simulate the 
interception of a surface-to-surface missile with a chemical 
warhead. An Arrow missile, serving as the target, was launched 
from a ship far offshore at 1100 [0900 GMT]. During the 
countdown leading up to the launching of the intercepting 
missile, a malfunctioning occurred, which prevented it from 
being fired. A built-in self-destruct system was then used to 
destroy the target missile. It is believed that the 
malfunctioning occurred in one of the ground control system's 
computers and had nothing to do with the missile itself. 
  Amir Oren, a commentator on military affairs, reported that 
sources at the Defense Ministry and Israel Aircraft Industries 
claimed that the experiment was unnecessary and was only carried 
out as a result of pressure from American experts also working 
on the project. Over the next few days, the project directors 
will continue to try and locate the problem and repair it. The 
next test launching is expected to take place in approximately 
six weeks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

