<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Kuwait </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Welcomes Sending UN Observers to Palestine </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303101094 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 0739 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0303101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] UN, 3 Mar -- The State of Kuwait has welcomed the 
initiative of UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali, showing 
readiness to send UN observers to occupied Palestinian 
territories. Kuwait said that it would be appropriate for the 
International Committee of the Red Cross to have special 
responsibility for civilians living under Israeli occupation 
with a view to ensuring their safety. 
  In his address to the UN Security Council during a debate on 
the situation in occupied Arab territories last night, Muhammad 
Abu al-Hasan, Kuwait's permanent representative at the United 
Nations, stressed the need to disarm Israeli settlers, some of 
whom had perpetrated the vile massacre in Ibrahim's mosque in 
Hebron last Friday. 
  The Kuwaiti representative said that the Security Council 
had 
to make Israel responsible for protecting Palestinians from the 
recklessness of those who wanted to hinder the peace process. 
He said that settlers had to be disarmed and the extremists 
among them had to be put under constant surveillance. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

