<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Rejects Arab Parties' Threats to Stop Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0303144994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1400 GMT 3 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0303144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin says it is unthinkable 
for a government relying on only 58 Knesset members to continue 
making decisions on extremely crucial issues in the life of the 
state. Rabin rejected threats by the Arab parties that they will 
cease to support the government if Tzomet joins the government 
coalition. Our correspondent in the north Yo'av Aviv reports 
that the prime minister was speaking at Kibbutz Ginnosar at the 
end of a meeting with Beduins from the north on the memorial day 
for Yig'al Allon. 
  Yitzhaq Rabin says the Palestinians' demand to open up the 
agreements for renegotiation in the wake of the massacre in 
Hebron is unacceptable, because if agreements are reopened after 
two months, what sense will be there to future agreements? Our 
correspondent adds that the prime minister explained that before 
the famous handshake with 'Arafat, he turned to the PLO leader 
and told him in connection with the signing of the agreement 
that this will be very difficult, and 'Arafat replied: I know. 

</TEXT>

