<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Rejects PLO Demands To Disarm Settlers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0203165794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1600 GMT 2 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0203165794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin says the longer the 
peace talks are halted, the more difficult it will be to resume 
them and the more complicated the situation on the ground will 
become. 
  Speaking to the Foreign Press Association, Rabin rejected 
the 
PLO's demands for more radical action against the Israeli 
settlers in the territories. Jack Katzenell reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Katzenell] Prime Minister Rabin made an 
impassioned appeal to the Palestinian leadership not to allow 
the late Barukh Goldstein to succeed in his aim of halting the 
peace process by means of the atrocity at the Hebron mosque. 
These are crucial days, Rabin said, and much will depend on how 
quick the negotiations are resumed. 
  [Rabin] The longer it will be dragged, the more it will be 
difficult to resume them, and the situation on the ground will 
be complicated. I believe that at this stage, the leadership on 
both sides -- the Palestinian and us -- has to stand up, to 
overcome pain, sorrow, and agony, and to understand that the 
real solution is in the political field. 
  [Katzenell] Rabin rejected Palestinian demands for the 
disarming of all the settlers. For decades the settlers have 
been the object of Palestinian terrorism, Rabin said, and even 
since the Oslo agreement, they have been the victims of 
terrorist attacks by the organizations opposed to the peace. 
  [Rabin] In coping with terror and violence, there were 
Palestinian victims, mainly in confrontations with the IDF 
[Israel Defense Forces] and other security forces, but terror by 
Israelis, killing, was very rare, if at all. 
  [Katzenell] Rabin also rejected suggestions that the 
settlers be evacuated from down-town Hebron. In his view, this 
would mean accepting the Palestinian demand for immediate 
negotiations on the future of the settlements, and that would be 
a breach of the Declaration of Principles. If we reopen signed 
agreements after only five months, Rabin said, what value will 
there be to any new agreements that we sign with the 
Palestinians. [end recording] 
  [Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew at 1600 GMT on 2 March adds: 
"Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin today warned against the 
involvement of Russia in the peace process without coordination 
with the Americans. Rabin said that parties to the negotiations 
might take advantage of the absence of a Russian-U.S. 
cooperation. 
  ["Speaking to foreign reporters, the prime minister said 
Israel will continue imposing the closure on the territories for 
as long as Israel believes it necessary. He added that the 
attorney general is examining the possibility of issuing 
additional detention orders against Kakh activists in the 
territories. Our correspondent Yiftah El'azar reports that 
Rabin further said: I have taken all the necessary steps to 
prevent a massacre in Hebron, to the best of my discretion and 
with the best means I had at my disposal."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

