<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on 'Arafat Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0203194894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1850 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0203194894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 2 Mar (MENA)--A highly-placed Palestinian 
source has stated that Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat has 
sent a number of proposals to the Israeli Government in an 
attempt to end the crisis resulting from the massacre at the 
Ibrahimi Mosque in Hebron in the occupied West Bank and return 
the Palestinian and Israeli delegations to the negotiating 
table. Sa'ib 'Urayqat, head of the Palestinian delegation to 
the Washington peace talks, will hand these proposals to the 
Israelis today. This source disclosed that the proposals, on 
which agreement was reached after the Palestinian leaders met on 
Sunday and Monday, include: 
  First, disarming the Israeli settlers and allowing an 
international presence [tawajud dawli] in the self-rule areas. 
  In a message to Israeli Prime Minister Rabin, which 'Urayqat 
will deliver, 'Arafat pointed out that these proposals are in 
line with the Declaration of Principles agreement. He said that 
the Cairo agreement provides that the Israeli army will protect 
the settlements while the Palestinian police will be responsible 
for security in the self-rule areas. The source said that 
'Arafat's proposals did not specify the type of international 
presence, UN forces or observers, but was content with the 
phrase "international presence." 
  The Palestinian source said that the second proposal 
requests 
restructuring certain settlements that are close to Palestinian 
population centers or those where extremist Jews live, such as 
the Netzarim settlement near Gaza, which 'Arafat proposed 
merging with the Gush Qatif settlement in south Gaza and Qiryat 
Arba' in Hebron. 'Arafat also proposed that Palestinians 
purchase these settlements. The Palestinian source noted that 
the third proposal requests Israel stop expropriating Arab land 
and building new settlements. He pointed out that 'Arafat has 
become convinced that the current crisis between Israel and the 
PLO can only be solved through direct dialogue between them, not 
by bringing other parties into the crisis. He said that 
intensive diplomatic efforts are under way in Cairo, Washington, 
and other capitals to convince both parties to reach a 
compromise and return to the negotiating table. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

