<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Urges EU To Push for Palestinian Protection </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0203161594 Paris AFP in English 1504 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0203161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, March 2 (AFP) -- PLO chief Yasir 'Arafat, in 
"agony" over the Hebron massacre, urged touring Greek Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias to push for international protection 
for Palestinians, Greek officials said Wednesday [2 March]. 
  Papoulias, current chairman of European Union's Ministerial 
Council, told reporters here the Council may be asked to provide 
European troops to an international protection force for the 
Israeli-occupied territories. 
  Papoulias, a long-time friend of 'Arafat, is to brief the 
Council next Monday to report the results of his tour of 
Tunisia, Jordan, Israel, Egypt and Syria. 
  The minister said he contacted several European colleagues 
after his talks here late Tuesday with the PLO chief to tell 
them of 'Arafat's demands. 
  An aide to Papoulias added that 'Arafat was "in agony" over 
the massacre and its consequences for negotiations aimed at 
launching the autonomy accord, which is almost three months 
behind schedule. 
  He "was not very talkative, kept hammering his 
preconditions" 
for restarting the autonomy talks, particularly "security 
guarantees and the disarming of the settlers." 
  Papoulias told 'Arafat that the European Union was "making 
every effort to ensure that the dialogue goes on." 
  "The tragic events of Hebron have created a new situation. 
It will have to be overcome through new measures," Papoulias 
said. 
  The Greek foreign minister also discussed the Hebron 
massacre 
and the autonomy talks with Tunisian President Ben Ali and 
Foreign Minister Habib Ben Yahya. 
  Papoulias was to visit Tel Aviv later Wednesday to meet with 
Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres, who has held several 
negotiating sessions with 'Arafat. 
  The PLO has spurned a call from U.S. President Bill Clinton 
to hold snap negotiations to finalise an autonomy deal with 
Israel, while Jordan, Lebanon and Syria broke off talks with 
Israel in support. 
  'Arafat said Tuesday he would insist on UN guarantees to 
protect the Palestinians before resuming peace talks. 
  'Arafat's "bottom line" included the dispatch of 
international peacekeepers, disarming the settlers and 
dismantling some settlements. 
  In New York, the UN Security Council was still struggling 
over a resolution on the massacre while Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali pushed for a UN presence to keep the peace in the 
territories. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

